006\u201310) (repurposed airing, Fridays at 7PM Eastern, of the NBC series; started airing Friday, September 29, 2006)<ref name=HeroesNBC>{{cite web|title=Heroes on NBC|url=http://www.nbc.com/heroes/|accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref>\n* ''[[Surface (TV series)|Surface]]'' (2005\u201306)\n* ''[[Passions]]'' (1999\u20132008)<ref name=PassionsEnd>{{cite web|title=NBC Passions soap opera moved to direcTV, cancelled|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/passions-nbc-soap-headed-for-directv/|accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref>\n* ''[[Chuck (TV series)|Chuck]]'' (2007\u201312)<ref name=ChuckFans>{{cite web|title=Chuck fan site|url=http://chucktv.net/|accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref><ref name=ChuckYvonne>{{cite news|title=Chuck star Yvonne Strahovski interview with Huffington Post|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/morgan-glennon/yvonne-strahovski-discuss_b_3329491.html|accessdate=May 30, 2013 | first=Morgan|last=Glennon|date=May 24, 2013}}</ref>\n* ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'' (2004\u201310)\n* ''[[Spartacus (TV series)|Spartacus]]'' (2010\u201313) (originally aired on [[Starz]])\n\n==TZGZ programming==\n{{Main|TZGZ}}\n\n===Current programming===\n====Original====\n* ''[[Happy Tree Friends]]'' (2020-present), co-production with [[Working Title Films|WT 2 Productions]], [[Universal Animation Studios]], [[Universal 1440 Entertainment]] and [[Universal Television]].\n\n====Acquired====\n* ''[[Gary and His Demons]]'' (2019)\n* ''Purgatony'' (2020)\n* ''Don't Feed the Humans'' (2020)\n* ''Hell Den'' (2020)\n* ''Science'' (2020)\n\n===Upcoming programming<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/01/syfy-ramps-up-animation-push-first-original-series-pilot-orders-tzgz-block-1202830104/|title=Deadline|last=|first=|date=January 17, 2020|website=Deadline|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 25, 2020}}</ref>===\n====Original====\n* ''Magical Girl Friendship Squad'' (Summer 2020)\n* ''[[Happy Tree Friends]]'' (2020-present)\n\n====Acquired====\n* ''[[The Cyanide & Happiness Show]]'' (February 2020)\n\n==Syfy miniseries==\n* ''[[5ive Days to Midnight]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Alice (TV miniseries)|Alice]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Ascension (miniseries)|Ascension]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Battlestar Galactica (TV miniseries)|Battlestar Galactica]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Childhood's End (miniseries)|Childhood's End]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[Dark Kingdom: The Dragon King]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Farscape: The Peacekeeper Wars]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Firestarter 2: Rekindled|Firestarter: Rekindled]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Frank Herbert's Dune]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Frank Herbert's Children of Dune]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Knights of Bloodsteel]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Legend of Earthsea (TV miniseries)|Legend of Earthsea]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Neverland (miniseries)|Neverland]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Riverworld (2010 film)|Riverworld]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Taken (TV miniseries)|Taken]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[The Triangle (miniseries)|The Triangle]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Lost Room]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Tin Man (TV miniseries)|Tin Man]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[The Phantom (miniseries)|The Phantom]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Treasure Island (2012 TV miniseries)|Treasure Island]]'' (2012)\n\n==Syfy original films==\n* See [[List of Sci Fi Pictures original films]].\n\n==Anime shown on Syfy==\n{{Anchor|Anime}} <!-- This section is linked from redirect \"[[Ani-Monday]]\" -->\n[[File:Saturday Anime.png|thumb|The Saturday Anime logo as it appeared on the Sci Fi Channel website, circa the late 1990s.]]\n\nFor most of the 1990s, Syfy showed [[anime]] films, although they had to be edited in order to be shown on basic cable. The channel's longest running animation block, referred to as Saturday Anime, aired at the start of the channel's broadcast day each Saturday morning. In 2007, Syfy reintroduced anime to their programming via the \"Ani-Monday\" block. In 2008 the block was shifted to Tuesday; in 2010, to Thursday; and after June 9, 2011, disappeared abruptly, along with the Anime section of the Syfy.com website.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2011-05-27/u.s-syfy-channel-lists-no-more-anime-after-june-9|title=U.S. SyFy Channel Lists No More Anime After June 9|publisher=|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.syfy.com/anime Syfy.com/Anime: 404, R.I.P.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110508164801/http://www.syfy.com/anime/ |date=2011-05-08 }}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[8 Man|8 Man After]]''\n* ''[[Adieu Galaxy Express 999]]''\n* ''[[Akira (1988 film)|Akira]]'' ([[Streamline Pictures]] dub)\n* ''[[Appleseed (2004 film)|Appleseed]]''\n* ''[[Appleseed (OVA)]]''\n* ''[[Armitage III: Poly-Matrix]]''\n* ''[[Black Jack (manga)|Black Jack: The Movie]]''\n* ''[[Black Magic M-66]] ''\n* ''[[Casshan: Robot Hunter]]''\n* ''[[Chrono Crusade]]''\n* ''[[Dead Leaves]]''\n* ''[[Demon City Shinjuku]]''\n* ''[[Descendants of Darkness]]''\n* ''[[Dominion (manga)|Dominion: Tank Police]]'' (edited)\n* ''E.Y.E.S. of Mars''\n* ''[[Fatal Fury: The Motion Picture]]''\n* ''[[Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within]]''\n* ''[[Galaxy Express 999 (film)|Galaxy Express 999]]''\n* ''[[Gall Force (original series)|Gall Force: Eternal Story]]''\n* ''[[Ghost in the Shell (1995 film)|Ghost in the Shell]]''\n* ''[[Ghost in the Shell: Stand Alone Complex - Solid State Society]]''\n* ''[[Green Legend Ran]]''\n* ''[[Gurren Lagann]]''\n* ''[[Highlander: The Search for Vengeance]]''\n* ''[[Iria: Zeiram the Animation]]''\n* ''[[Kai Doh Maru]]''\n* ''[[Karas: The Prophecy]]''\n* ''[[Karas: The Revelation]]''\n* ''[[Lensman (anime)|Lensman]]''\n* ''[[Lily C.A.T.]]''\n* ''[[Macross Plus]]''\n* ''[[MD Geist]]''\n* '' [[MD Geist |MD Geist II: Death Force]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam 00]]''\n* ''[[Monster (manga)|Monster]]''\n* ''[[Negadon: The Monster from Mars]]''\n* ''[[The New Adventures of Gigantor]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skooldays.com/categories/saturday/sa1660.htm|title=The New Adventures of Gigantor: Old Memories|website=www.skooldays.com|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[Ninja Scroll]]''\n* ''[[Noein: To Your Other Self]]''\n* ''[[Now and Then, Here and There]]''\n* ''[[Odin: Photon Sailer Starlight|Odin - Starlight Mutiny]]''\n* ''[[Perfect Blue]]''\n* ''[[Project A-ko]]''\n* ''[[Project A-ko: Grey Side/Blue Side]]''\n* ''[[Psychic Wars]]''\n* ''[[Rave Master]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-01-19/u.s-sci-fi-channel-to-run-rave-master-fantasy-anime|title=U.S. Sci Fi Channel to Run Rave Master Fantasy Anime|publisher=|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[Read or Die]]''\n* ''[[Record of Lodoss War]]'' (1990 OVA series, first three episodes only)\n* ''[[Robot Carnival]]''\n* ''[[Roujin Z]]''\n* ''[[Star Blazers |Star Blazers: The Quest for Iscandar]]''\n* ''[[Strait Jacket]]''\n* ''[[Street Fighter Alpha: The Animation]]''\n* ''[[Street Fighter Alpha: Generations]]''\n* ''[[Street Fighter II: The Animated Movie]]''\n* ''[[Street Fighter II V]]''\n* '' Sword for Truth''\n* ''[[Tactics (manga)|Tactics]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi the Movie: Tenchi Muyo in Love]]''\n* ''[[Tokko (manga)|Tokko]]''\n* ''[[Urusei Yatsura 2: Beautiful Dreamer]]''\n* ''[[Vampire Hunter D (1985 film)]]''\n* ''[[Vampire Wars]]''\n* ''[[Venus Wars]]''\n* ''[[Virus Buster Serge]]''\n* ''[[The Wicked and the Damned: A Hundred Tales of Karma]]''\n* ''[[X (1996 film)|X]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Announced, unrealized projects==\n;2002<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-main.html?2002-06/07/12.00.film | title = SCI FI Slate Announced | publisher = Sci Fi Wire, (Syfy/Sci Fi Channel) | date = April 3, 2002 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20020606112646/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2002-04%2F03%2F14.00.sfc | archivedate = June 6, 2002 | access-date = March 12, 2020 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n* ''The Chronicles of Amber'': Four-hour miniseries based on [[Roger Zelazny]]'s [[The Chronicles of Amber|10-volume series]], scripted by [[Richard Christian Matheson]], with Tom Patricia of Patriarch Pictures as executive producer.\n* ''Colosseum'': [[television film|made-for-TV-movie]] in which modern-day fight promoter Tommy Pettigrew finds himself transported in time to the [[Colosseum]] of [[Rome]] in the year AD 95, with a script by [[Sam Egan]]. Directed by [[Mario Azzopardi]] and executive produced by Egan, Azzopardi, and Matt Loze.\n* ''The Forever War'': Four-hour miniseries, scripted by [[John Fasano]] and based on [[Joe Haldeman]]'s [[The Forever War|novel of that name]]. Executive producers were [[Richard Edlund]], along with Peter Sussman and Ed Gernon for [[Alliance Atlantis]].\n* ''Myst'': Four-hour miniseries based on the video game ''[[Myst]]''. A [[Mandalay Pictures|Mandalay Television Pictures]] production, executive produced by Elizabeth Stephen with Rand Miller and Susan Bonds of Cyan, in association with [[Sony Pictures Television|Columbia Tri Star Domestic Television]] and distributed through USA Cable Entertainment.\n* ''On the Seventh Day'': Seven-hour miniseries set in 2850 in an overcrowded world in which the government has assigned people one day a week to live, while spending the remaining six days in [[cryogenic suspension]], from writer and executive producer [[Gary Sherman (director)|Gary Sherman]] and USA Cable Entertainment.\n* ''Quantum Leap'': Syfy announced development of a two-hour [[television film]] based on ''[[Quantum Leap]]'' that would have served as a [[backdoor pilot]] for a possible new series, with series creator [[Donald P. Bellisario]] returning as executive producer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2002-07/09/12.30.sfc |title=New Leap, Tremors On Sci-Fi |publisher=[[Syfy]] |date=July 9, 2002 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060709102508/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2002-07%2F09%2F12.30.sfc |archivedate=July 9, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n;2003\n* ''1000 Days'': A live-action [[television film|made-for-TV-movie]] and [[backdoor pilot]] based on the [[Marvel Comics]] series ''[[Strikeforce: Morituri]]'', about near-future soldiers who gain enhanced abilities but die 1,000 days later. Written by [[Art Marcum and Matt Holloway]], it was a [[Shine America#Reveille Productions|Reveille Productions]] and [[Marvel Studios]] co-production executive produced by Reveille head [[Ben Silverman]] and [[Marvel Studios]]' [[Avi Arad]] and [[Rick Ungar]].<ref name=SciFiMarvel-Jan2003>{{cite web|url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2003-01/10/10.00.sfc|title=SCI FI Adapts Marvel Series|date=January 3, 2003|publisher=Sci Fi Wire (Sci Fi Channel)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030208000307/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2003-01%2F10%2F10.00.sfc|archive-date=February 8, 2003|access-date=March 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* ''Alien Blood'': TV-movie of a human rebellion when an invading alien army demands that one million people be sacrificed. Produced by UFO Films.<ref name=scifiunveils />\n* ''Brother Voodoo'': A live-action made-for-TV-movie and [[backdoor pilot]] based on the [[Marvel Comics]] supernatural character [[Brother Voodoo]]. Hans Rodionoff was announced to write the screenplay, set in [[New Orleans]], of this Reveille Productions and Marvel Studios co-production executive produced by Reveille head Ben Silverman and Marvel Studios' Avi Arad and Rick Ungar.<ref name=SciFiMarvel-Jan2003 />\n* ''Dead Rail'': A made-for-TV-movie set aboard a bullet train headed to [[Las Vegas]] on its inaugural run, and a detective who must battle hostile aliens. Written by Brian Smith, \"founder of SciFi.com's Seeing Ear Theatre\", and produced by Glow Worm.<ref name=scifiunveils>{{cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2003-07/09/11.30.sfc |title=SCI FI Unveils Film Slate |publisher=Sci Fi Wire (Sci Fi Channel) |date=July 9, 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030804004032/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2003-07%2F09%2F11.30.sfc |archivedate=August 4, 2003 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* ''The Twelve'': A [[miniseries]], based on a concept by [[David Pirie]], about an FBI agent who finds evidence that the world will end on the [[twelfth day of Christmas]]. With [[Martin Scorsese]] and producer [[Barbara De Fina]] as executive producers, with Cappa/De Fina Productions in conjunction with Adrian Bate and Zenith Entertainment Ltd., it was scheduled to debut in December 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2003-07/11/12.00.sfc |title=Scorsese Comes to SCI FI |publisher=Sci Fi Wire (Sci Fi Channel) |date=July 11, 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030804010609/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2003-07%2F11%2F12.00.sfc |archivedate=August 4, 2003 |access-date=March 12, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n;2004\n* ''Kyra'': [[David Twohy]], co-screenwriter and director of ''[[Pitch Black (film)|Pitch Black]]'' and writer-director of its sequels ''[[The Chronicles of Riddick]]'' and ''[[Riddick (film)|Riddick]]'', said in June 2004 he was writing the story basis for a Sci-Fi Channel [[television film|made-for-TV-movie]] pilot based on the ''Riddick'' character Kyra.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2004-06/07/12.15.sfc | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20040607195540/http://www.scifi.com/scifiwire/art-sfc.html?2004-06%2F07%2F12.15.sfc | title = Twohy Readies ''Kyra'' Pilot | publisher = Sci Fi Wire (SciFi.com) | date = June 7, 2004 | archivedate = June 7, 2004 | access-date = March 12, 2020 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n;2005<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.aoltv.com/2005/04/14/new-slot-of-original-sci-fi-shows-on-the-way/ | title =New slew of original Sci Fi shows on the way| publisher = AOL TV | date= April 14, 2005|archivedate= May 18, 2015|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150518100627/http://www.aoltv.com/2005/04/14/new-slot-of-original-sci-fi-shows-on-the-way/|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* ''Barbarian Chronicles'': A half-hour animated ensemble comedy show created by [[Brendon Small]]. To be co-produced by [[David Letterman]]'s [[Worldwide Pants]] production company.\n* ''Dallas in Wonderland'': A half-hour reality series hosted by [[Dallas Campbell]], where he attempts to succeed at a series of sci Fi challenges.\n* ''Heroes Anonymous'': A live-action show based on the [[Bongo Comics Group]] comic about a group of superheroes that start a support group.\n* ''Seriously Baffling Mysteries'': A half-hour mockumentary hosted by Jonathan Frankle, which goes in search of the paranormal on a shoestring budget.\n* ''Those Who Walk In Darkness'': A live-action adaptation of the [[Those Who Walk In Darkness|novel]] by [[John Ridley]].\n* ''Time Tunnel'': A remake of the 1960s [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] sci-fi series ''[[The Time Tunnel]]''. Co-produced with [[Fox Television Studios]] and [[Kevin Burns]] and Jon Jashni of Synthesis Entertainment. Written by [[John Turman]].\n* ''Tomorrow's Child'': A series about a girl who received extraordinary powers after being saved by an alien. Produced by [[NBC Universal Television Studio]] and Gary Foster's Horseshoe Bay Productions.\n* ''Urban Arcana'': A live-action series based on the [[Urban Arcana|role-playing game]]. Aron Coleite was to write and Gary A. Randall and [[Rockne O'Bannon]] were to produce in association with Fox Television Studios.\n* \"Return of The Thing\": A planned four-hour mini-series that would've served as a sequel to John Carpenter's 1982 horror classic [[The Thing (1982 film)]]. [[Frank Darabont]] was on board as an executive producer on the series, which would have taken place in both Antarctica and a small town in New Mexico. Though the project fell through, concept art and a screenplay was released.\n\n;2018\n* ''[[Tremors (franchise)#Untitled television series .28TBA.29|Tremors]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title='Tremors\u2019 Reboot Starring Kevin Bacon From Blumhouse Gets Syfy Pilot Order|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/kevin-bacon-tremors-reboot-pilot-order-syfy-blumhouse-1202120429/|website=Deadline|accessdate=June 26, 2017}}</ref>: On November 28, 2015, it was reported that Universal Television and [[Blumhouse Productions]] were developing a new ''Tremors'' TV series and that Kevin Bacon would reprise his role of Valentine McKee for the first time in the series since the first movie.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trumbone|first1=Dave|title=Kevin Bacon to Battle Graboids in \u2018Tremors\u2019 TV Series|url=https://collider.com/kevin-bacon-tremors-tv-series/|website=Collider.com|accessdate=30 November 2015}}</ref> In August 2017, it was announced that [[Vincenzo Natali]] would direct the pilot<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title='Tremors\u2019: Vincenzo Natali To Direct Syfy-Blumhouse Reboot Starring Kevin Bacon|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/tremors-vincenzo-natali-direct-syfy-blumhouse-reboot-kevin-bacon-1202154317/|date=August  22, 2017|website=Deadline|accessdate=August  22, 2017}}</ref> which would be written by showrunner Andrew Miller<ref name=\"aj\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.abqjournal.com/1073407/kevin-bacon-back-in-the-saddle-for-tremors-pilot.html?amp=1 |title=Kevin Bacon back in the saddle for \u2018Tremors\u2019 pilot |last=Gomez |first=Adrian |date=2017-10-04 |website=[[Albuquerque Journal]] |access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref> with filming taking place from late October 2017 through November 2017.<ref name=\"aj\"/> On April 28, 2018, it was announced that Syfy had passed on the pilot.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=\u2018Tremors\u2019 Reboot Pilot Starring Kevin Bacon Not Going Forward At SyFy|url=https://deadline.com/2018/04/tremors-reboot-pilot-dead-kevin-bacon-star-syfy-1202378796/|date=April 28, 2018|website=Deadline|accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Syfy (United Kingdom) programmes]]\n* [[List of comedy science fiction movies]]\n* [[List of science fiction television programs]]\n* [[Chiller (TV channel)|Chiller]]\n* [[TZGZ]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://www.syfy.com/movies Syfy's Original Movies]\n* [https://www.syfy.com/schedule Syfy's Schedule]\n* [http://innermind.com/sfc/index.html ''The Inner Mind'''s Sci-Fi Channel schedule lists]&nbsp;\u2014 dates as far back as 1994 and then some\n\n{{Syfy Shows|state=expanded}}\n{{Programs}}\n\n[[Category:Syfy original films| ]]\n[[Category:Syfy original programming| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of television series by network|Sci Fi Channel]]\n", "name_user": "Alphius", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUpcoming programs:Fixed formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_programs_broadcast_by_Syfy"}
{"title_page": "Savings account", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=October 2013}}\n{{Banking |accs/cards |image=SampleBankbook.png |caption=The [[passbook]] was the traditional record of savings account transactions before the use of the internet.}}\n\nA '''savings account''' is a [[bank account]] at a [[retail banking|retail bank]] whose features include the requirements that only a limited number of withdrawals can take place, it does not have cheque facilities, it has limited transfer facilities and cannot be overdrawn. Transactions on savings accounts are widely recorded in a [[passbook]], and [[bank statement]]s may not be provided. Savings accounts normally pay [[interest]]. A number of countries require savings accounts to be protected by [[deposit insurance]] and some countries provide a government guarantee for at least a portion of the savings account balance.\n\n==Regulations==\n===United States===\nIn the [[United States]], Sec. 204.2(d)(1) of [[Regulation D (FRB)]] limits withdrawals from savings accounts to 6 pre-authorized transfers or withdrawals (excluding withdrawals via an [[automated teller machine]]) per month or a statement cycle of at least four weeks. There is no limit to the number of deposits into the account. Violations of the regulation may result in a service charge, or may result in the account being changed to a checking account.\n\nRegulation D sets smaller reserve requirements for savings account balances. In addition, customer\u2019s can plan withdrawals to avoid fees and earn interest, which contributes to more stable savings account balances on which banks can lend. A savings account linked to a checking account at the same financial institution can help avoid fees due to overdrafts and reduce banking costs.<ref>{{cite web | title=Banking: Savings Accounts 101 | url=http://www.investopedia.com/university/banking/banking7.asp | author=Amy Fontinelle}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n* [http://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/savingsaccount.asp Savings Account Definition | Investopedia]\n* [https://www.money-rates.com/savings/what-is-a-savings-account.htm Savings Accounts Regulation D | MoneyRates.com]\n* [https://www.nerdwallet.com/blog/banking/savings-accounts-basics/ What is a Savings Account - NerdWallet]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Savings Account}}\n[[Category:Bank account]]\n[[Category:Interest-bearing instruments]]\n{{Bank-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=October 2013}}\n{{Banking |accs/cards |image=SampleBankbook.png |caption=The [[passbook]] was the traditional record of savings account transactions before the use of the internet.}}\n\nA '''savings account''' is a [[bank account]] at a [[retail banking|retail bank]] whose features include the requirements that only a limited number of withdrawals can take place, it does not have cheque facilities, it has limited transfer facilities and cannot be overdrawn. Transactions on savings accounts are widely recorded in a []passbook]], and [[bank statement]]s may not be provided. Savings accounts normally pay [[interest]]. A number of countries require savings accounts to be protected by [[deposit insurance]] and some countries provide a government guarantee for at least a portion of the savings account balance.\n\n==Regulations==\n===United States===\nIn the [[United States]], Sec. 204.2(d)(1) of [[Regulation D (FRB)]] limits withdrawals from savings accounts to 6 pre-authorized transfers or withdrawals (excluding withdrawals via an [[automated teller machine]]) per month or a statement cycle of at least four weeks. There is no limit to the number of deposits into the account. Violations of the regulation may result in a service charge, or may result in the account being changed to a checking account.\n\nRegulation D sets smaller reserve requirements for savings account balances. In addition, customer\u2019s can plan withdrawals to avoid fees and earn interest, which contributes to more stable savings account balances on which banks can lend. A savings account linked to a checking account at the same financial institution can help avoid fees due to overdrafts and reduce banking costs.<ref>{{cite web | title=Banking: Savings Accounts 101 | url=http://www.investopedia.com/university/banking/banking7.asp | author=Amy Fontinelle}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n* [http://www.investopedia.com/terms/s/savingsaccount.asp Savings Account Definition | Investopedia]\n* [https://www.money-rates.com/savings/what-is-a-savings-account.htm Savings Accounts Regulation D | MoneyRates.com]\n* [https://www.nerdwallet.com/blog/banking/savings-accounts-basics/ What is a Savings Account - NerdWallet]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Savings Account}}\n[[Category:Bank account]]\n[[Category:Interest-bearing instruments]]\n{{Bank-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Enthusiast01", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Savings_account"}
{"title_page": "Fred and Barney Meet the Thing", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Fred and Barney Meet the Thing\n| image                    = Fred and Barney Meet the Thing.jpg\n| genre                    = [[Animation]]\n| creator                  = \n| director                 = [[Ray Patterson (animator)|Ray Patterson]]<br>[[George Gordon (animator)|George Gordon]]<br>[[Carl Urbano]]\n| starring                 = \n| voices                   = [[Henry Corden]]<br>[[Mel Blanc]]<br>[[Jean Vander Pyl]]<br>[[Gay Autterson]]<br>Joe Baker<br>Wayne Morton<br>[[Marilyn Schreffler]]\n| based_on = {{based on|[[The Flintstones]]||[[William Hanna]]|[[Joseph Barbera]]}}<br>{{based on|[[Thing (comics)|Thing]]||[[Stan Lee]]|[[Jack Kirby]]}}\n| narrated                 = \n| theme_music_composer     = \n| opentheme                = \n| endtheme                 = \n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_episodes             = 13 (26 segments of ''The Thing'')\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = William Hanna<br>Joseph Barbera\n| producer                 = [[Alex Lovy]]\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 60 minutes\n| company                  = [[Hanna-Barbera Productions|Hanna-Barbera]]<br>[[Marvel Comics Group]]\n| distributor              = [[Taft Broadcasting]]<!-- Only add the original distributor of the show if the show has one, as Infobox Television says \" The names of the original distribution company or companies.\" If the show doesn't have a distributor, leave it blank. -->\n| network                  = [[NBC]]\n| picture_format           = \n| audio_format             = \n| first_aired              = {{start date|1979|09|08}}\n| last_aired               = {{end date|1979|12|01}}\n| preceded_by              = ''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]''\n| followed_by              = ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]''\n| related                  = \n| website                  = \n| num_series               = \n}}\n\n'''''Fred and Barney Meet the Thing''''' is an American [[Saturday-morning cartoon|animated]] package show and a [[list of television spin-offs|spin-off]] of ''[[The Flintstones]]'' produced by [[Hanna-Barbera]] which aired on [[NBC]] from September 8, 1979 to December 1, 1979.<ref name=Woolery>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Children's Television: The First Thirty-Five Years, 1946-1981 |date=1983 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-1557-5  |url=https://archive.org/details/childrenstelevis0000wool/page/108/mode/2up |accessdate=14 March 2020 |page=108}}</ref>\n\nThe series contained the following two segments:\n\n*''[[The New Fred and Barney Show]]'' (a revival of ''The Flintstones'') \u2013 one episode, 30 minutes\n*''The Thing'' (based on the [[Marvel Comics]] superhero [[Thing (comics)|Thing]]) \u2013 two episodes, 11 minutes each\n \nDespite the show's title, the two segments remained separate and did not crossover with one another. The characters of [[Fred Flintstone]], [[Barney Rubble]] and [[Thing (comics)|Thing]] were only featured together during the opening title sequence and in brief bumpers between segments.<ref name=Daytime>{{cite book |last1=Hyatt |first1=Wesley |title=The Encyclopedia of Daytime Television |date=1997 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=978-0823083152 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofda00hyat/page/160/mode/2up|accessdate=19 March 2020|page=160}}</ref> The unusual combination of a Marvel superhero and ''The Flintstones'' was possible because, at this time, [[Marvel Comics]] owned the rights to several Hanna-Barbera franchises and were, in fact, publishing comic books based upon them; ''The Flintstones'' was one of these.\n\nFor the 1979\u201380 season, the series was expanded to a 90-minute timeslot with the addition of ''[[The New Shmoo]]'' episodes and broadcast under the new title '''''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]'''''.\n\nLike many animated series created by Hanna-Barbera in the 1970s, the show contained a [[Laugh track#Making their own|laugh track]], one of their last productions to do so.\n\n==The Thing==\nThe first segment, a very loose adaptation of [[Marvel Comics]]' character the [[Thing (comics)|Thing]], consisted of stories following the adventures of a scrawny, red-headed teenager named Benjy Grimm (voiced by Wayne Morton)<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=210}}</ref> who changes into the monstrous and mighty Thing (voiced by Joe Baker) by touching together two magic rings and reciting the words \"Thing Ring, do your thing!\", releasing an explosion of energy that causes orange rocks to hurl in from every direction and transform him into the stone-skinned superhero. When the Thing spoke, his good-naturedly gruff [[Brooklyn]]-accented voice was based on that of comedian [[Jimmy Durante]].\n\nThe stories centered mostly around Benjy at Centerville High School with his friends, the beautiful brunette Betty Harkness (voiced by [[Marilyn Schreffler]]), her snooty rich boyfriend Ronald Radford (voiced by [[John Erwin]]), and Betty's blond [[tomboy]] younger sister Kelly (voiced by Noelle North), with minimal adult supervision provided by teacher Miss Twilly (voiced by [[Marilyn Schreffler]]). Only Kelly and her scientist father Dr. Harkness (voiced by [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]]) know Benjy's secret identity.\n\nWhen not battling various [[mad scientist]]s and getting involved in [[Scooby-Doo]]-style mysteries, the Thing spent most of his time using his superhuman strength to protect his pals from everyday dangers and the nasty [[practical joke]]s of leather-clad bully Spike (voiced by [[Art Metrano]]) and his biker buddies Stretch and Turkey in the [[Yancy Street Gang]].\n \nOther members of the [[Fantastic Four]] did not appear in the show, and the portrayal of the Thing and his origin story differed greatly from the original comics.<ref>{{cite news|title= Fantastic Four on TV|newspaper= [[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=|url= http://uk.tv.ign.com/articles/797/797130p2.html|accessdate=September 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\nTwenty-six 11-minute episodes of ''The Thing'' were produced; two shorts aired per show.\n\n''The Thing'' segments are owned by [[WarnerMedia]], through [[Hanna-Barbera]], [[Warner Bros. Animation]] and [[Warner Bros. Family Entertainment]], but the character is owned by [[The Walt Disney Company]] due to their purchase of Marvel Comics in late 2009.\n\n===Other appearances===\nIn ''[[Future Foundation|FF]]'' #8, [[Ant-Man]] and [[Dragon Man]] give pink-haired rock star turned reluctant superhero Darla Deering her own Thing Rings to summon Ben Grimm's old rocky Thing-bodied [[powered exoskeleton|exoskeleton]] and become the bubble-helmeted Miss Thing, saying \"Thing Rings, do your thing--\".<ref>''[[Future Foundation|FF]]'' #8, writer: [[Matt Fraction]], artist: [[Mike Allred]]</ref>\n\n===Episodes===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#FF681F; width:20px\"| {{Abbr|N\u00ba|Number}}\n! style=\"background:#FF681F; width:20px\"| {{Abbr|Ep|Episode}}\n! style=\"background:#FF681F\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#FF681F; width:135px\"| Original air date\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 1\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 1\n| Title               = The Picnic Panic\n| OriginalAirDate     = {{Start date|1979|9|8}}\n| ShortSummary        = Benjy and his friends attend their high school picnic at the Centerville Picnic Grounds, but when the Yancy Street Gang shows up at the picnic and causes trouble, The Thing must save the day.\n| LineColor           = #FF681F\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber       = 2\n| EpisodeNumber2      = 2\n| Title               = Bigfoot Meets the Thing\n|